<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-245-608  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 245 608.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  May 1 1989 v216 n18 pS28(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Broadband: Who wants it? (telecommunication technology) (COServices Special supplement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Warr, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Broadband technology means that today's fantasies can actually betransformed into tomorrow's realities.andP;  For example, ISDN(integrated services digital network) features that would allowinteractive use of voice, data and video signals can be achievedusing high-speed (155M-bps) packet switching that can provide thenecessary transmission and switch capabilities.andP;  Broadband isassociated with packet switching and with fiber optics; narrowbandis based in copper networks and depends on circuit switching.andO;When they consider deploying fiber, BOCs (Bell operatingcompanies) currently must balance technological capabilitiesagainst revenue-generating services.andP;  Broadband services are notyet popularized, and with no demand for them, it can be difficultto justify costs to stockholders and regulators.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BroadbandFiber opticsTelecommunicationsISDNMarketing StrategyProduct DevelopmentBell Regional Holding CompaniesTelephone systemsCommunications Service SuppliersOutlookCost Benefit AnalysisStrategic Planning.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>